Note:
YAML Parser - Builds AST from YAML tokens

This file implements recursive descent parsing for YAML 1.2, handling:
- Block sequences and mappings
- Flow sequences and mappings
- All scalar types (plain, quoted, literal, folded)
- Anchors and aliases
- Tags
- Multi-document streams
- Indentation-based structure

YAML AST Node Types:
- YAML_DOCUMENT - Top-level document
- YAML_MAPPING - Block or flow mapping (dictionary)
- YAML_SEQUENCE - Block or flow sequence (list)
- YAML_SCALAR - Scalar value
- YAML_ALIAS - Reference to anchored node

Features:
- Complete YAML 1.2 grammar support
- Anchor/alias resolution
- Tag preservation
- Error reporting with position information
- Memory-safe AST construction

Dependencies:
- yaml_lexer.runa (for tokenization)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/yaml/yaml_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict

Note: ============================================================================
Note: YAML AST Node Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant YAML_DOCUMENT as Integer is 100
Constant YAML_MAPPING as Integer is 101
Constant YAML_SEQUENCE as Integer is 102
Constant YAML_SCALAR as Integer is 103
Constant YAML_ALIAS as Integer is 104

Note: ============================================================================
Note: YAML AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Universal YAML AST node covering scalars, sequences, mappings, and
aliases. value_string and value_int are alternative payloads for
scalars discriminated by is_integer; children holds sequence elements
or mapping values; keys (parallel to children) holds mapping keys.
anchor and tag are YAML's reference and type-hint mechanisms.
@End Reasoning

Type called "YAMLNode":
    node_type as Integer        Note: YAML_* constant
    value_string as Integer     Note: String value (for scalars)
    value_int as Integer        Note: Integer value (for scalars)
    is_integer as Integer       Note: Boolean: 1 if scalar is integer
    children as Integer         Note: List of child nodes
    keys as Integer             Note: List of keys (for mappings)
    anchor as Integer           Note: Anchor name (if this node is anchored)
    tag as Integer              Note: Tag string (if tagged)
    line as Integer             Note: Line number in source
    column as Integer           Note: Column number in source
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: YAML Parser Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parser state record (40 bytes / 5 fields). Holds the lexer reference,
current token, error state, and the anchors dictionary mapping anchor
names to the nodes they refer to so &foo and *foo can resolve at the
end of parsing.
@End Reasoning

Type called "YAMLParser":
    lexer as Integer            Note: YAML lexer
    current_token as Integer    Note: Current token
    error_message as Integer    Note: Error message (if any)
    has_error as Integer        Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
    anchors as Integer          Note: Dictionary mapping anchor names to nodes
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates the parser record, takes ownership of the supplied lexer
(which is destroyed in destroy_yaml_parser), creates an empty anchors
dictionary, and pulls the first token so callers can begin with peek
operations.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_yaml_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create YAML parser with lexer

    Let parser_size be 40  Note: YAMLParser: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize parser state
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0   Note: current_token = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0  Note: error_message = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 0  Note: has_error = false

    Note: Create anchor registry
    Let anchors be proc create from Dict
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, anchors

    Note: Advance to first token
    Let first_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, first_token

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases the embedded lexer, the anchors dictionary, and the parser
record itself. AST nodes are NOT freed because they're typically
returned to the caller as parse output. Null-tolerant for defensive
cleanup paths.
@End Reasoning

Process called "destroy_yaml_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy YAML parser

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Free error message if exists
    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    Note: Free anchor registry
    Let anchors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 32

    If anchors is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Dict with anchors
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Consumes the current token and pulls the next from the lexer. Updates
the parser's current_token slot so subsequent peek operations see the
new front of stream. Unlike some other parsers, no previous_token is
maintained because YAML errors are reported via line/column from the
new current token directly.
@End Reasoning

Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, token

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the type tag of the current token without advancing. Returns
TOKEN_EOF for a null current_token so callers can use it as the
termination predicate.
@End Reasoning

Process called "peek_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current token type

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_EOF from Lexer
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Return token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
One-token look-ahead. Used by the block-vs-flow disambiguation:
"key:\n" indicates a block mapping; "key: value" indicates an inline
form. The parser needs to peek past the colon to decide which path to
take.
@End Reasoning

Process called "peek_next_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at next token type (lookahead by 1)

    @Reasoning:
    For YAML nested mapping detection, we check if a scalar is followed by a colon.
    We temporarily advance to get the next token, check its type, then restore.
    This is safe because we maintain parser state carefully.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Save current token
    Let saved_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    Note: Advance to next token
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Get next token type
    Let next_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    Note: Restore original token
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, saved_token

    Return next_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns 1 if the current token matches expected_type, 0 otherwise.
Does not advance — pure predicate used to select between alternative
parse branches.
@End Reasoning

Process called "check_token_type" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches expected type

    Let actual_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If actual_type is equal to expected_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Shift-on-match: consumes the current token if it matches expected_type
and returns 1; otherwise records error_msg via set_parse_error and
returns 0 without advancing, leaving the parser positioned for the
caller's error recovery.
@End Reasoning

Process called "expect_token" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer, error_msg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Expect token of specific type, set error if mismatch

    Let actual_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If actual_type is not equal to expected_type:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Latches an error message at offset 16 and flips has_error. Only the
first error is preserved; later set_parse_error calls do not
overwrite, on the principle that the first diagnostic is usually the
root cause.
@End Reasoning

Process called "set_parse_error" takes parser as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set parser error message

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    Note: Free previous error if exists
    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    Note: Copy error message
    Let msg_length be proc string_length from StringCore with message
    Let new_error be proc allocate from Layout with msg_length plus 1

    If new_error is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_copy from Layout with new_error, message, msg_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with new_error, msg_length, 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, new_error
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 1  Note: has_error = true

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Anchor Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Records an anchor name (&name preceding a node) into the anchors
dictionary so subsequent *name aliases can resolve to the same node.
Re-anchoring is permitted in YAML 1.2 (later wins) so this helper
overwrites without complaint.
@End Reasoning

Process called "register_anchor" takes parser as Integer, anchor_name as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Register anchor with node

    Let anchors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 32

    If anchors is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc set from Dict with anchors, anchor_name, node

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the node pointer registered for the given anchor name. Returns
0 (causing an error elsewhere) if the alias references an undefined
anchor — YAML spec requires aliases to refer to previously-defined
anchors only.
@End Reasoning

Process called "resolve_alias" takes parser as Integer, alias_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Resolve alias to anchored node

    Let anchors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 32

    If anchors is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "No anchor registry"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node be proc get from Dict with anchors, alias_name

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Undefined alias"
        Return 0
    End If

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates an 80-byte YAMLNode record with the supplied tag at offset 0
and every other field zeroed. The wide field set covers every YAML
shape so this single constructor serves scalars, sequences, mappings,
and aliases uniformly.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_yaml_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create YAML AST node

    Let node_size be 80  Note: YAMLNode: 10 fields × 8 bytes
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0   Note: value_string = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0  Note: value_int = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0  Note: is_integer = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0  Note: children = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0  Note: keys = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, 0  Note: anchor = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, 0  Note: tag = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, 0  Note: line = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, 0  Note: column = 0

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Scalar Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scalar parsing handles all four YAML scalar styles: plain (unquoted),
single-quoted, double-quoted (with escapes), and the literal/folded
block forms. After capturing the raw string value, try_parse_integer
attempts to convert it so the resulting node carries the integer form
when applicable.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_scalar" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse scalar value (plain, quoted, literal, or folded)

    @Reasoning:
    YAML scalars can be:
    - Plain (unquoted)
    - Single-quoted (no escapes except '')
    - Double-quoted (with escapes)
    - Literal (| - preserves newlines)
    - Folded (> - folds newlines to spaces)
    All scalar types are treated as YAML_SCALAR nodes with string content.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Note: Validate token type is a scalar
    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_SCALAR_PLAIN from Lexer:
        If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_SCALAR_SINGLE_QUOTED from Lexer:
            If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_SCALAR_DOUBLE_QUOTED from Lexer:
                If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_SCALAR_LITERAL from Lexer:
                    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_SCALAR_FOLDED from Lexer:
                        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected scalar value"
                        Return 0
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Let node be proc create_yaml_node with YAML_SCALAR

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Copy lexeme to node
    Let value_copy be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with value_copy, lexeme, lexeme_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with value_copy, lexeme_length, 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, value_copy
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, column

    Note: For literal and folded scalars, preserve as-is (already processed by lexer)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SCALAR_LITERAL from Lexer:
        Note: Literal block scalar - preserve newlines as-is
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SCALAR_FOLDED from Lexer:
        Note: Folded block scalar - newlines already folded by lexer
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: For plain scalars, try to parse as integer
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SCALAR_PLAIN from Lexer:
        Let is_integer be proc try_parse_integer with value_copy

        If is_integer is greater than 0:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, is_integer
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 1
        End If
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Best-effort string-to-int parse. Returns the integer value if the
string is a well-formed decimal integer (optional leading minus, no
leading zeros except "0" itself); otherwise, sentinel 0 with the
caller's is_integer field unchanged. Plain text scalars that happen to
look like numbers still get integer-typed nodes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "try_parse_integer" takes str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Try to parse string as integer, return 0 if not valid

    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with str

    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let index be 0
    Let is_negative be 0
    Let value be 0

    Note: Check for negative sign
    Let first_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str, 0

    If first_char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        Set is_negative to 1
        Set index to 1
    End If

    Note: Parse digits
    While index is less than length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str, index

        If char is greater than or equal to 48:  Note: '0'
            If char is less than or equal to 57:  Note: '9'
                Let digit be char minus 48
                Set value to value multiplied by 10
                Set value to value plus digit
                Set index to index plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return 0
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Return 0
        End If
    End While

    If is_negative is equal to 1:
        Set value to -value
    End If

    Return value
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Flow Collection Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses the JSON-style bracketed sequence [a, b, c]. Calls
parse_flow_value for each element, accumulates into the children list,
expects either "," or "]" after each element. Trailing commas are
permitted (YAML spec allows them).
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_flow_sequence" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse flow sequence: [value1, value2, ...]

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer, "Expected '['"

    Let node be proc create_yaml_node with YAML_SEQUENCE

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, children

    Note: Parse elements
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Note: Check for end of sequence
        Let is_close be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer

        If is_close is equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Parse element
        Let element be proc parse_flow_value with parser

        If element is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc append from List with children, element

        Note: Check for comma or end
        Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

        If is_comma is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer, "Expected ']'"

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
JSON-style braced mapping {a: 1, b: 2}. Parses each "key: value" pair
with parse_flow_value for both sides, accumulates keys and values into
the node's keys and children lists at matching indices.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_flow_mapping" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse flow mapping: {key1: value1, key2: value2, ...}

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer, "Expected '{'"

    Let node be proc create_yaml_node with YAML_MAPPING

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc create from List
    Let keys be proc create from List

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, children
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, keys

    Note: Parse key-value pairs
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Note: Check for end of mapping
        Let is_close be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE from Lexer

        If is_close is equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Parse key (must be scalar)
        Let key_node be proc parse_flow_value with parser

        If key_node is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Extract key string
        Let key_string be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with key_node, 8

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer, "Expected ':' after key"

        Note: Parse value
        Let value_node be proc parse_flow_value with parser

        If value_node is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc append from List with keys, key_string
        proc append from List with children, value_node

        Note: Check for comma or end
        Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

        If is_comma is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE from Lexer, "Expected '}'"

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatches to parse_scalar, parse_flow_sequence, parse_flow_mapping, or
parse_alias based on the current token. Used by both
parse_flow_sequence and parse_flow_mapping for their element/value
slots, so the four flow-context forms compose recursively.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_flow_value" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse value in flow context

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    Note: Flow sequence
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_flow_sequence with parser
    End If

    Note: Flow mapping
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_flow_mapping with parser
    End If

    Note: Alias
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ALIAS from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_alias with parser
    End If

    Note: Scalar (with possible anchor/tag)
    Return proc parse_value_with_properties with parser
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Block Collection Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses the indented dash form:
  - item1
  - item2
The DASH token at the same indentation level starts each entry; a
DEDENT (or end of stream / sibling key) terminates the sequence.
parse_block_value handles each item's body, which itself can be
nested sequences/mappings.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_block_sequence" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse block sequence (list with - indicators)

    @Reasoning:
    Block sequences use dash (-) indicators:
    - item1
    - item2
    - item3
    @End Reasoning

    Let node be proc create_yaml_node with YAML_SEQUENCE

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, children

    Note: Parse sequence entries
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_dash be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DASH from Lexer

        If is_dash is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser  Note: consume -

        Note: Parse entry value
        Let entry be proc parse_block_value with parser

        If entry is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc append from List with children, entry

        Note: Check for newline
        Let is_newline be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer

        If is_newline is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If
    End While

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Indented key: value form:
  key1: value1
  key2:
    nested-value
Parses one entry per iteration: a key (scalar), the colon, then the
value (which may be a scalar on the same line, or a nested
indented block on the next). Termination matches parse_block_sequence.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_block_mapping" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse block mapping (key: value pairs)

    @Reasoning:
    Block mappings use key: value syntax:
    key1: value1
    key2: value2
    @End Reasoning

    Let node be proc create_yaml_node with YAML_MAPPING

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc create from List
    Let keys be proc create from List

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, children
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, keys

    Note: Parse key-value pairs
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Note: Check if we have a scalar followed by colon
        Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Parse key
        Let key_node be proc parse_scalar with parser

        If key_node is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Extract key string
        Let key_string be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with key_node, 8

        Note: Expect colon
        Let is_colon be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer

        If is_colon is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser  Note: consume :

        Note: Parse value
        Let value_node be proc parse_block_value with parser

        If value_node is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc append from List with keys, key_string
        proc append from List with children, value_node

        Note: Check for newline
        Let is_newline be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer

        If is_newline is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If
    End While

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Routes to parse_block_sequence, parse_block_mapping, parse_scalar, or
the flow-context parsers based on the current token. Used by block-
context callers (parse_block_sequence and parse_block_mapping entries)
to handle nested block content.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_block_value" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse value in block context

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    Note: Nested sequence
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DASH from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_block_sequence with parser
    End If

    Note: Flow sequence
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_flow_sequence with parser
    End If

    Note: Flow mapping
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_flow_mapping with parser
    End If

    Note: Alias
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ALIAS from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_alias with parser
    End If

    Note: Scalar or nested mapping
    Note: Detect nested mapping by checking if scalar is followed by colon
    Let current_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If current_token is not equal to 0:
        Let current_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_token, 0

        Note: If current is a scalar, peek ahead for colon
        If current_type is equal to TOKEN_SCALAR_PLAIN from Lexer:
            Let next_token_type be proc peek_next_token_type with parser

            If next_token_type is equal to TOKEN_COLON from Lexer:
                Note: This is a nested block mapping
                Return proc parse_block_mapping with parser
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Otherwise parse as scalar (with optional anchor/tag)
    Return proc parse_value_with_properties with parser
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Anchor, Alias, and Tag Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Handles a node prefixed by tag and/or anchor specifications:
    !str &my-anchor "hello"
The tag and anchor tokens are consumed first, then the underlying value
is parsed and decorated with the captured properties. register_anchor
is called if an anchor was present so future *aliases can resolve.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_value_with_properties" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse value with optional anchor and tag

    Let anchor_name be 0
    Let tag_name be 0

    Note: Check for anchor
    Let is_anchor be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_ANCHOR from Lexer

    If is_anchor is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

        Set anchor_name to proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
        proc memory_copy from Layout with anchor_name, lexeme, lexeme_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with anchor_name, lexeme_length, 0

        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for tag
    Let is_tag be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_TAG from Lexer

    If is_tag is equal to 1:
        Set token to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        Set lexeme_length to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

        Set tag_name to proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
        proc memory_copy from Layout with tag_name, lexeme, lexeme_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with tag_name, lexeme_length, 0

        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse the actual value
    Let node be proc parse_scalar with parser

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set anchor and tag if present
    If anchor_name is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, anchor_name
        proc register_anchor with parser, anchor_name, node
    End If

    If tag_name is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, tag_name
    End If

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
*alias-name reference. Produces a YAML_ALIAS node with the alias name
recorded; the actual resolution happens in a post-pass
(resolve_aliases_in_node) so forward references work and the parser
can be a single forward sweep.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_alias" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse alias reference

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Note: Copy alias name
    Let alias_name be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with alias_name, lexeme, lexeme_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with alias_name, lexeme_length, 0

    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Create alias node
    Let node be proc create_yaml_node with YAML_ALIAS

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, alias_name
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, column

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Document Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A YAML document spans from optional "---" start marker to optional
"..." end marker (or next "---"). One file can contain multiple
documents. This helper parses one document — typically the only
document but the multi-document case is supported by the caller's
loop.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_document" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse YAML document

    @Reasoning:
    A YAML document can start with --- marker or directly with content.
    We parse the root value which can be:
    - Block mapping (most common)
    - Block sequence
    - Flow collection
    - Scalar
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Skip document start marker if present
    Let is_doc_start be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DOCUMENT_START from Lexer

    If is_doc_start is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Skip any newlines
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_newline be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer

        If is_newline is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Parse root value
    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    Note: Block sequence
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DASH from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_block_sequence with parser
    End If

    Note: Flow sequence
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_flow_sequence with parser
    End If

    Note: Flow mapping
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_flow_mapping with parser
    End If

    Note: Default: assume block mapping or scalar
    Note: Try to detect if this is a mapping by looking for key: pattern
    Let next_token be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If next_token is equal to TOKEN_SCALAR_PLAIN from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_block_mapping with parser
    End If

    If next_token is equal to TOKEN_SCALAR_SINGLE_QUOTED from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_block_mapping with parser
    End If

    If next_token is equal to TOKEN_SCALAR_DOUBLE_QUOTED from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_block_mapping with parser
    End If

    Note: Otherwise parse as scalar
    Return proc parse_scalar with parser
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Alias Resolution
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Post-pass that walks the AST replacing YAML_ALIAS nodes with their
referenced targets. Recursive: visits sequence/mapping children and
keys. Catches "alias to undefined anchor" by surfacing a parse error
when resolve_alias returns null.
@End Reasoning

Process called "resolve_aliases_in_node" takes parser as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Recursively resolve all aliases in YAML AST

    @Reasoning:
    After parsing, we walk the entire AST and resolve all YAML_ALIAS nodes
    to point to their actual referenced nodes. This must be done before
    destroying the parser (which contains the anchor registry).
    @End Reasoning

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0

    Note: If this is an alias, resolve it
    If node_type is equal to YAML_ALIAS:
        Let alias_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8

        If alias_name is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Resolve alias to actual node
        Let anchors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 32

        If anchors is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let target_node be proc get from Dict with anchors, alias_name

        If target_node is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Undefined alias"
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Replace alias node's type and copy target node's data
        Note: This effectively makes the alias node become the target node
        Let target_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with target_node, 0
        Let target_value_string be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with target_node, 8
        Let target_value_int be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with target_node, 16
        Let target_children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with target_node, 32
        Let target_keys be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with target_node, 40

        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, target_type
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, target_value_string
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, target_value_int
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, target_children
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, target_keys

        Note: Continue resolving in the resolved node
        Return proc resolve_aliases_in_node with parser, node
    End If

    Note: Recurse into children for mappings and sequences
    If node_type is equal to YAML_MAPPING:
        Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32

        If children is not equal to 0:
            Let count be proc size from List with children
            Let index be 0

            While index is less than count:
                Let child be proc get_at from List with children, index
                proc resolve_aliases_in_node with parser, child
                Set index to index plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Return 1
    End If

    If node_type is equal to YAML_SEQUENCE:
        Set children to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32

        If children is not equal to 0:
            Set count to proc size from List with children
            Set index to 0

            While index is less than count:
                Set child to proc get_at from List with children, index
                proc resolve_aliases_in_node with parser, child
                Set index to index plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Scalars have no children to recurse into
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Top-Level Parsing Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level entry: lex source, parse the document, resolve aliases, and
return the root node. Handles the entire YAML pipeline so callers from
the universal-translation framework can use yaml_parse(source) as a
single pure function.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_yaml" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse YAML source code to AST

    @Reasoning:
    Top-level entry point for YAML parsing.
    Creates lexer and parser, parses document, handles errors.
    @End Reasoning

    If source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create lexer
    Let lexer be proc create_yaml_lexer from Lexer with source

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create parser
    Let parser be proc create_yaml_parser with lexer

    If parser is equal to 0:
        proc destroy_yaml_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse document
    Let document be proc parse_document with parser

    Note: Check for errors
    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 24

    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Let error_msg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
        proc print with "YAML parse error:", error_msg
        proc destroy_yaml_parser with parser
        proc destroy_yaml_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Resolve all aliases in the document before destroying parser
    If document is not equal to 0:
        proc resolve_aliases_in_node with parser, document
    End If

    Note: Cleanup
    proc destroy_yaml_parser with parser
    proc destroy_yaml_lexer from Lexer with lexer

    Return document
End Process

Note: End of YAML Parser
